From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Wed, 11 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: dual all-CPU self-dump at 8s+9s,
 panic at 10s on migration deadlock

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop(). Three confirmed patterns:

  Pattern A -- nested re-entrancy (LB path):
    active_load_balance_cpu_stop()
      -> finish_task_switch() -> run_balance_callbacks()
        -> sched_balance_rq() -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()
    while already executing inside stop_two_cpus() / multi_cpu_stop().
    Signature in Sec6: one CPU is_active=YES, others is_active=NO.

  Pattern B -- concurrent stop_machine exhaustion:
    N concurrent stop_machine() calls (e.g. aarch64_insn_patch_text_cb
    racing with LB or other callers) exhaust all cpu_stopper threads.
    Callback issues nested stop_machine() which cannot be serviced.
    Signature in Sec6: ALL CPUs show is_active=YES.

  Pattern G -- WALT module init race (observed, kworker/2:2):
    kworker/2:2 executing walt_init [sched_walt] calls stop_machine()
    to atomically initialise per-CPU WALT data structures. Inside
    queue_stop_cpus_work(), kworker is preempted by migration/N (RT
    prio 98) mid-loop. stop_cpus_in_progress=true but not all CPUs
    have received their work. The preempted kworker's CPU never acks
    PREPARE; multi_cpu_stop spins forever.

    Observed stack:
      #4 queue_stop_cpus_work   <- preempted here by migration/N
      #5 stop_machine_cpuslocked
      #6 stop_machine
      #7 walt_init [sched_walt]
      #8 process_one_work
      #9 worker_thread
      Signature: CPU2 is_active=NO curstate=NONE (kworker never ran
      multi_cpu_stop); remaining CPUs stuck in PREPARE.

The Qualcomm msm_watchdog bark fires at ~11s. This patch detects the
deadlock at 8s, collects FIRST all-CPU call stacks at detection, then
triggers a SECOND all-CPU call stack dump immediately before panic at
10s -- giving two independent stack snapshots in kmsg for comparison.
panic() triggers ramdump for a third, definitive capture.

==========================================================================
Design: dual all-CPU self-dump + ktime-bounded wait + panic at 10s
==========================================================================

Why self-dump instead of trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() IPI:
  trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() sends IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to each CPU and
  waits up to 10 seconds for each response. CPUs in DISABLE_IRQ state
  have local IRQs disabled -- the IPI cannot be delivered -- so the
  caller blocks for 10s per unresponsive CPU. On an 8-core device this
  can be 70s, far beyond the 11s watchdog bark. Ref:
  patchew.org/linux/fb0b7a92-d371-4510-80c4-25a57f2c4f3d@paulmck-laptop/

  Self-dump (this patch): each CPU that detects the timeout (IRQs ON =
  PREPARE state) calls dump_stack() on itself synchronously. No IPI.
  No cross-CPU wait. All dumps appear in kmsg without coordination
  overhead.

  CPUs in DISABLE_IRQ state cannot detect the timeout (jiffies frozen,
  time_after() false) and cannot self-dump. The owner logs a timeout
  message for those CPUs in Sec5. Their stacks are fully preserved in
  the ramdump captured by panic().

Why two dumps:
  First dump  (T=8s): Captures the exact state at deadlock onset.
              Proves all PREPARE CPUs are stuck in multi_cpu_stop().
  Second dump (T=~8.8s): Confirms no progress in the 0.8s interval.
              Proves it is a true livelock, not a transient delay.
              Two independent kmsg records strengthen root-cause analysis
              when bisecting across ramdumps from different builds.

Non-owner second dump protocol:
  After completing Phase 1 (first dump), non-owner PREPARE CPUs spin
  polling stopper_second_dump_trigger. When the owner sets this flag
  (at T=8.8s), each non-owner calls dump_stack() a second time, sets
  stopper_second_dump_done, then enters a final spin until panic().
  DISABLE_IRQ CPUs cannot poll the flag and do not participate in the
  second dump; their stacks are in the ramdump.

Timeline:
  T=0s    deadlock begins

  T=8s    time_after() fires on PREPARE-state CPUs (IRQs ON, jiffies live)
          Phase 1 (ALL detecting CPUs, before cmpxchg):
            (a) stopper_snapshot_self()  -- write own percpu slot
            (b) FIRST dump_stack()       -- "CPU%u FIRST dump_stack at 8s"
            (c) atomic_set(stopper_first_dump_done, 1)

          atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, cpu):
            ONE CPU wins --> dump owner: runs Sec1-6, triggers second dump
            ALL others   --> spin polling stopper_second_dump_trigger

  T=8s    Sec1: owner outer stopper fn + caller
  T=8s    Sec2: multi_stop_data state
  T=8s    Sec3: CPU masks
  T=8s    Sec4: owner stopper state (detailed)
  T=8-8.8s Sec5: owner polls stopper_first_dump_done for all online CPUs
                 (DUMP1_WINDOW_MS = 800ms deadline from t_detect)
  T=8.8s  Sec6: print all percpu snapshots

  T=8.8s  SECOND DUMP TRIGGER:
            owner sets stopper_second_dump_trigger = 1
            ALL non-owner PREPARE CPUs see flag, call SECOND dump_stack()
            owner calls SECOND dump_stack()
            all set stopper_second_dump_done = 1
  T=8.8-9.6s owner polls stopper_second_dump_done for all online CPUs
                 (DUMP2_WINDOW_MS = 1600ms deadline from t_detect)

  T=10s   panic() -- ramdump captured
            First  dump in kmsg:  T=8s  (deadlock onset)
            Second dump in kmsg:  T=~8.8s (pre-panic confirmation)
            Ramdump stacks:       T=10s (definitive, all CPUs)
  T=11s   Qualcomm bark_time -- 1s margin

==========================================================================
Per-CPU done tracking
==========================================================================

stopper_first_dump_done  (DEFINE_PER_CPU atomic_t, zero at boot):
  Writer: each detecting CPU sets 1 after FIRST dump_stack() (Phase 1c).
  Reader: owner polls in Sec5 with ktime deadline.

stopper_second_dump_trigger (global atomic_t, ATOMIC_INIT(0)):
  Writer: owner sets 1 after Sec6 to signal non-owners.
  Reader: non-owner PREPARE CPUs poll in their spin loop.
  smp_wmb() before atomic_set() ensures all Sec1-6 output is ordered
  before the trigger is visible to spinning CPUs.

stopper_second_dump_done (DEFINE_PER_CPU atomic_t, zero at boot):
  Writer: each CPU sets 1 after SECOND dump_stack().
  Reader: owner polls with ktime deadline before panic().

==========================================================================
Timing constants (all relative to t_detect = ktime at T=8s)
==========================================================================

  STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES = 8 * HZ    (8000ms at HZ=250 = 2000 jiffies)
    jiffies-based detection threshold. Fires only in PREPARE state
    (IRQs ON, timer tick active). In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: jiffies frozen,
    time_after() permanently false. No false positive.

  STOPPER_DUMP1_WINDOW_MS = 800ULL
    ktime deadline for first dump collection (Sec5).
    t_detect + 800ms = T=8.8s. PREPARE CPUs are done near-instantly.
    DISABLE_IRQ CPUs time out and are logged as "see ramdump".

  STOPPER_DUMP2_TRIGGER_MS = 800ULL
    ktime from t_detect at which owner triggers the second dump.
    = DUMP1_WINDOW_MS: second dump starts immediately after Sec5.
    t_detect + 800ms = T=8.8s.

  STOPPER_DUMP2_WINDOW_MS = 1600ULL
    ktime deadline for second dump collection.
    t_detect + 1600ms = T=9.6s. Non-owners have 800ms after trigger.

  STOPPER_PANIC_WINDOW_MS = 2000ULL
    ktime from t_detect to panic(). T=8s + 2s = T=10s.
    Qualcomm bark_time ~11s -> 1s margin.

==========================================================================
Code placement -- two insertion points (Clang 19 build correctness)
==========================================================================

INSERT POINT A (after includes, before struct cpu_stopper ~line 180):
  Constants, stopper_dump_owner, stopper_first_dump_done,
  stopper_second_dump_trigger, stopper_second_dump_done,
  struct stopper_cpu_snapshot, stopper_snapshot_self().
  -- NOTHING here references cpu_stopper or struct multi_stop_data.

INSERT POINT B (after struct multi_stop_data ~line 210):
  stopper_state_names[], stopper_state_name()
  stopper_dump_one_cpu()        -- uses per_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper, cpu)
  stopper_dump_msdata()         -- uses struct multi_stop_data *
  stopper_wait_for_first_dumps() -- polls stopper_first_dump_done
  stopper_wait_for_second_dumps() -- polls stopper_second_dump_done
  stopper_print_other_snapshots() -- reads stopper_snapshot slots
  stopper_deadlock_dump()       -- orchestrates Sec1-6 + dual dump + panic
  -- All types fully defined here.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'. Clang 19 warns on signed/
unsigned mismatch at cpumask_test_cpu() and per_cpu_ptr() call sites.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Position C unconditional detection (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

  do {
    if (curstate < msdata->state) { ... }
    if (is_active)       ack_state(msdata);         /* A */
    else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
        touch_nmi_watchdog(); rcu_momentary_eqs();  /* B: not in PREPARE */
    }
    /* C: ALL CPUs, ALL states, every iteration -- our detection point */
    if (!timed_out && time_after(now_j, ...)) { ... }
  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

In PREPARE: position B is never reached (condition false), IRQs stay ON,
jiffies advance, time_after() fires at T=8s.
In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: position B IS reached, IRQs off, jiffies frozen,
time_after() false -- no false positive.

==========================================================================
Upstream context
==========================================================================

Upstream partially addressed a related deadlock in 2018:
  commit 0b26351b910f ("stop_machine, sched: Fix migrate_swap() vs.
  active_balance() deadlock", Peter Zijlstra) -- fixed spinlock
  contention in cpu_stop_queue_work(). Zijlstra noted: "I'm not
  entirely sure there isn't more dragons here." This patch addresses
  the remaining dragon: cpu_stopper_thread is single-threaded per-CPU
  and cannot service inner callbacks while executing outer ones.

Piggin June 2024 series (lkml.org/lkml/2024/6/25/589):
  stop_machine_yield() already present in 6.12 tree (backported).
  No conflict with this patch.

rcu_momentary_eqs() stall warnings:
  During the Sec5 2-dump window (T=8s to T=9.6s, ~1.6s) the non-owner
  PREPARE CPUs spin without calling rcu_momentary_eqs(). This may
  generate RCU CPU stall warnings in dmesg. These are benign -- the
  kernel is about to panic(). The stall warnings may appear between the
  first and second dump in the log; they can be ignored in analysis.

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================

- Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
- No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
- Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
- ktime_get(): <linux/ktime.h> -- newly added include
- atomic_t / atomic_set / atomic_read / atomic_cmpxchg: already present
- DEFINE_PER_CPU: <linux/percpu.h> -- already present
- No trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() (IPI hazard with DISABLE_IRQ CPUs)

